MySpace Music President Holt Exits as News Corp. Seeks Buyer for Website

-- B y   A n d y   F i x m e r
-- 
2011-02-25T00:24:45Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-24/myspace-music-president-courtney-holt-to-step-down-correct-.html
Myspace Music President Courtney Holt said he is stepping down from his management role at the
social network that  News Corp . is preparing to sell.  Holt will be an adviser to Myspace and parent company News
Corp., and remain the music operation’s board, Mike Jones, chief
executive officer of Beverly Hills-based Myspace, said today in
a note to employees. Jones will oversee Myspace Music operations
on an interim basis.  Holt is a top candidate to run  Google Inc .’s planned music
service, Dow Jones & Co.’s AllThingsD.com reported today.  Apple
Inc ., based in Cupertino, California, and London-based Spotify
Ltd. may also want to hire him, the site said. Holt departs
Myspace Music, a joint operation between News Corp.’s Myspace
and the biggest music labels, ahead of a possible sale of all or
part of the operation by News Corp.  New York-based News Corp., controlled by Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer  Rupert Murdoch , gained 20 cents, or 1 percent,
to $16.76 at 4 p.m. New York time in Nasdaq Stock Market
trading. The shares have risen 15 percent this year.  Allen & Co., the New York-based investment bank hired by
News Corp. to sell Myspace, is setting up meetings with
prospective buyers in March, the Wall Street Journal reported
today. About 20 companies, including financial firms, expressed
interest, the newspaper said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Andy Fixmer in  Los Angeles  at 
 afixmer@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Anthony Palazzo at   apalazzo@bloomberg.net  